all your problems, Oliver,

261
00:17:54,565 --> 00:17:56,415
but I just... I can't.

262
00:17:58,355 --> 00:18:02,359
But one thing I can do
is talk with you

263
00:18:02,935 --> 00:18:05,085
about everything that's going on.

264
00:18:06,291 --> 00:18:07,291
So what?

265
00:18:07,459 --> 00:18:09,240
Well, for one thing, maybe

266
00:18:09,365 --> 00:18:11,922
it will help you feel less alone.

267
00:18:12,047 --> 00:18:13,047
I am alone.

268
00:18:13,215 --> 00:18:15,509
And I'm not gonna get
to see you anymore.

269
00:18:15,634 --> 00:18:16,634
I know.

270
00:18:17,695 --> 00:18:21,395
And that's why I'm really glad
that we had this chance

271
00:18:22,475 --> 00:18:24,075
just to talk.

272
00:18:29,325 --> 00:18:32,441
Why don't you tell me about your week?
Let's begin there.

273
00:18:33,785 --> 00:18:35,685
Today was my last day at school.

274
00:18:37,015 --> 00:18:38,515
And how did that go?

275
00:18:39,195 --> 00:18:41,445
They had a going-away party for me.

276
00:18:41,955 --> 00:18:43,705
My teacher made brownies.

277
00:18:44,415 --> 00:18:46,122
Eric wasn't there, so that was good.

278
00:18:46,290 --> 00:18:47,748
Why wasn't Eric there?

279
00:18:48,065 --> 00:18:49,620
He was in the hospital.

280
00:18:49,745 --> 00:18:51,945
What's Eric doing in the hospital?

281
00:18:53,695 --> 00:18:55,495
He was lighting some M-80s

282
00:18:56,035 --> 00:18:58,092
and they exploded
and blew his pinkie off.

283
00:19:00,935 --> 00:19:03,597
That's pretty awful for Eric,
don't you think?

284
00:19:04,565 --> 00:19:06,851
Why do you think
he picked on you so much?

285
00:19:07,685 --> 00:19:11,105
Do you think it might have been because
he had so many problems of his own{\, you know}?

286
00:19:14,175 --> 00:19:15,175
Maybe.

287
00:19:15,605 --> 00:19:17,155
So how is Maya doing?

288
00:19:19,095 --> 00:19:21,045
She got me a going-away gift.

289
00:19:21,283 --> 00:19:22,933
Cool. What did she get?

290
00:19:26,585 --> 00:19:27,735
That's sweet.

291
00:19:30,825 --> 00:19:32,543
You're gonna miss her, right?

292
00:19:40,195 --> 00:19:41,645
I'll miss my house.

293
00:19:43,415 --> 00:19:46,865
Your dad told me that he came over today
to help you pack.

294
00:19:47,058 --> 00:19:48,058
How was that?

295
00:19:48,805 --> 00:19:49,805
Weird.

296
00:19:50,405 --> 00:19:53,505
Like he was living with us again,
except he wasn't.

297
00:19:55,895 --> 00:19:57,943
He and my mom
both started to cry a little.

298
00:19:58,455 --> 00:19:59,605
Both of them?

299
00:20:02,485 --> 00:20:03,782
So what was that like?

300
00:20:03,995 --> 00:20:05,045
I hated it.

301
00:20:06,085 --> 00:20:09,205
You know, once when I was
about your age, I saw my dad cry.

302
00:20:12,065 --> 00:20:14,463
He was having a big fight
with my mom.

303
00:20:14,895 --> 00:20:16,879
They were yelling at each other.

304
00:20:17,185 --> 00:20:19,035
I just wanted them to stop.

305
00:20:19,425 --> 00:20:21,425
I guess I wanted them to be...

306
00:20:22,615 --> 00:20:23,965
to be just happy.

307
00:20:24,725 --> 00:20:26,925
And it made me so pissed

308
00:20:27,205 --> 00:20:28,755
when I found out that...

309
00:20:29,815 --> 00:20:31,215
that they weren't.

310
00:20:33,425 --> 00:20:35,325
So what did you do?

311
00:20:36,480 --> 00:20:40,380
Well, I stayed pissed at them
for a long time.

312
00:20:42,035 --> 00:20:43,885
And then I realized that...

313
00:20:44,995 --> 00:20:48,051
even though
my mom and dad got upset,

314
00:20:48,176 --> 00:20:50,776
and they made
big mistakes sometimes,

315
00:20:52,875 --> 00:20:54,375
they still loved me.

316
00:20:56,645 --> 00:20:58,395
What am I supposed to do?

317
00:21:01,505 --> 00:21:03,940
If you're not getting
something that you need,

318
00:21:04,065 --> 00:21:05,065
tell them.

319
00:21:05,715 --> 00:21:08,055
If you don't understand why
something is happening, say:

320
00:21:08,180 --> 00:21:10,480
"Can you please explain this to me?"

321
00:21:11,215 --> 00:21:14,215
And if things get really
upsetting and confusing,

322
00:21:14,455 --> 00:21:15,455
call me.

323
00:21:16,325 --> 00:21:19,825
That way we can work together
to try and solve the problem.

324
00:21:28,155 --> 00:21:29,660
Does your son live far away?

325
00:21:33,445 --> 00:21:35,845
I go visit him on weekends.

326
00:21:37,065 --> 00:21:41,069
This Saturday I’m taking him to the air
and space museum in Washington, D.C.

327
00:21:41,945 --> 00:21:45,595
He likes to look at the rockets
and the satellites especially.

328
00:21:48,555 --> 00:21:49,596
Do you miss him?

329
00:21:51,635 --> 00:21:52,785
All the time.

330
00:21:53,755 --> 00:21:54,755
But, see,

331
00:21:55,345 --> 00:21:57,345
I'm with him whenever...

332
00:21:57,665 --> 00:21:59,065
whenever I can be.

333
00:22:02,106 --> 00:22:04,106
I'm always thinking about him.

334
00:22:05,735 --> 00:22:07,531
I mean, we talk on the phone
every day.

335
00:22:08,475 --> 00:22:10,725
So I get to hear what he has to say

336
00:22:11,675 --> 00:22:14,525
and I get to tell him
what's going on with me.

337
00:22:18,745 --> 00:22:21,253
That reminds me...
I've got to make a call.

338
00:22:24,235 --> 00:22:25,465
Can you give me a sec?

339
00:22:45,675 --> 00:22:48,075
- Hello.
- Hey, Oliver.

340
00:22:49,515 --> 00:22:51,115
It's Paul in Brooklyn.

341
00:22:52,415 --> 00:22:54,910
I just thought I'd check in
and see how...

342
00:22:55,035 --> 00:22:57,164
